Question 1

# reload chapter 3, exercise 5
dat <- knitr::load_cache('arm03-q05_', 'dat')

(a)

The model is given by:

\[ \begin{align} y_i &\sim \text{N} \left( \alpha_{j[i]} + \beta_{j[i]} x_i + Z_i \Pi, \sigma_y^2 \right) \\ \begin{matrix} \alpha_j \\ \beta_j \end{matrix} &\sim \text{N} \left( \begin{matrix} \mu_{\alpha} \\ \mu_{\beta} \end{matrix}, \begin{pmatrix} \sigma_{\alpha}^2 & \rho \sigma_{\alpha} \sigma_{\beta} \\ \rho \sigma_{\alpha} \sigma_{\beta} & \sigma_{\beta}^2 \end{pmatrix} \right) \end{align} \]

where \(x_i\) is a measure of the professors beauty and \(Z_i\) contains indicators for whether the professor is female and whether the professor is a minority. In this case, the grouping variable course is created using the class* indicators; data with no indicator were dropped.

(b)

# rename outcome variable and create id
dat %<>%
  rename(ce = courseevaluation) %>%
  mutate(
    id = 1:n()
  )

# create course category?
category <- select(dat, id, starts_with("class"))
category %<>% gather(course, value, -id)
category %<>% filter(value != 0)
category$course %<>% str_remove_all("class")
category$course %<>% as.numeric()

# join back category
dat %<>% left_join(select(category, id, course), by = "id")

# drop course = NA
dat %<>% filter(!is.na(course))

# fit the model
reg <- lmer(
  ce ~ btystdave + female + minority + (1 + btystdave | course),
  data = dat
  )
display(reg)
## lmer(formula = ce ~ btystdave + female + minority + (1 + btystdave | 
##     course), data = dat)
##             coef.est coef.se
## (Intercept)  4.12     0.08  
## btystdave    0.09     0.07  
## female      -0.18     0.09  
## minority    -0.31     0.10  
## 
## Error terms:
##  Groups   Name        Std.Dev. Corr 
##  course   (Intercept) 0.33          
##           btystdave   0.17     0.59 
##  Residual             0.43          
## ---
## number of obs: 157, groups: course, 30
## AIC = 245.2, DIC = 203.4
## deviance = 216.3

In this model, the unexplained within-course variation has an estimated standard deviation of \(\sigma_{ce} = 0.43\), the estimated standard deviation of the course intercepts is \(\sigma_{course} = 0.33\) and the estimated standard deviation of the course slopes is \(\sigma_{bystdave} = 0.17\).

(c)

# coefficients
dat_coef <- coef(reg)$course %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "course") %>%
  mutate_at(vars(course), as.numeric)

# create new grouping
dat %<>%
  mutate(
    female_minority = case_when(
      female == 0 & minority == 0 ~ "White male",
      female == 0 & minority == 1 ~ "Minority male",
      female == 1 & minority == 0 ~ "White female",
      TRUE ~ "Minority female"
    )
  )
  
# plot
p <- ggplot() +
  geom_point(
    aes(x = btystdave, y = ce, colour = female_minority),
    data = dat
  ) +
  geom_abline(
    aes(intercept = `(Intercept)`, slope = btystdave),
    data = dat_coef
  ) +
  scale_colour_ipsum() +
  theme_ipsum() +
  labs(x = "Beauty score", y = "Evaluation score", colour = "Type") +
  facet_wrap(~course)
p

pdat <- bind_cols(
  coef(reg)$course[, 1], 
  ranef(reg)$course[, 1],
  .name_repair = "unique"
)
names(pdat) <- c("est", "se")

p <- ggplot(pdat, aes(x = factor(1:30), colour = factor(1:30))) +
  geom_point(aes(y = est)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = est - 2 * se, ymax = est + 2 * se)) +
  theme_ipsum() +
  labs(x = "Course", y = "Intercept") +
  guides(colour = F)
p

Question 2

(a)

One way to model this might be:

\[ \begin{align} y_i &\sim \text{N} \left( \mu + \alpha_{j[i]} + \sum_{l \in I}^3 \beta_{k[i]}^l, \sigma_y^2 \right) \\ \alpha_j &\sim \text{N} \left(0, \sigma_{\alpha}^2 \right) \\ \beta_k &\sim \text{N} \left(0, \sigma_{\beta}^2 \right) \end{align} \] where \(y_i\) is applicant \(i\)s combined score, \(\mu\) captures the overall average rating while \(\alpha_i\) and \(\beta_i^l\) capture the deviations from \(\mu\) attributable to applicant \(i\) and their three raters respectively.

(b)

One option would be to change the model for \(\beta_k\) to:

\[ \begin{align} \beta_k &\sim \text{N} \left(0, \sigma_k^2 \right) \\ \sigma_k &\sim \exp \left( \gamma_k \right) \end{align} \]
